Preheat your oven to 200°C and put a large #saucepan{} of water on to boil with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel!). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Trim the @green beans{150}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop the potato into the boiling water and simmer for ~{15-20%mins}.

> The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(stalks and all). Put half the parsley in a small #bowl{} and mix in the @panko breadcrumbs{10}, @Provencal herbs{1/2}, @olive oil{1} and season with @salt{}. Pop the @salmon fillets{2} skin side down on a #baking tray{} lined with #baking paper{}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Using the back of a #spoon{}, spread the @mayonnaise{1} over the top half of each fillet and then sprinkle over the crumb mixture.

Roast the salmon on the top shelf of your oven until cooked through and golden on top, ~{12-15%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: The salmon is cooked when opaque all the way through.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} over medium heat. Add the onion. Cook until soft, ~{7-10%mins}, stirring occasionally, then remove from the pan and keep to one side. Don't wash the pan - we'll use it later to cook the green beans.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan off the heat. Add a @butter{knob} and a splash of @milk{} (if you have any) and mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and stir in the cooked onion. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

Heat a splash of oil in your (now empty) frying pan on high heat. Stir-fry the green beans for ~{2%mins}. Add the garlic and season with @salt{}. Add the @water{75}. Pop a lid on the pan (or cover with #foil{}) and steam until just tender, ~{3-5%mins}. Drain any leftover water, then stir through the @balsamic vinegar{6} and @olive oil{1}.

Reheat the onion mash if necessary and spoon a generous amount onto your plate. Serve the salmon and garlicky green beans alongside. Drizzle the balsamic dressing from the beans around the plate and finish with a sprinkling of the remaining parsley. Enjoy!

> This recipe is a celebration of contrasts. The creamy mash is flavoured with sweet caramelised onion and sharp, salty cheese. Its pillowy softness is the perfect counterpart to succulent salmon in a crispy coating of herbed breadcrumbs. Comfort food of the highest order but with a side of garlicky green beans to keep things light.

> Step 2 MOD: If you've opted to get salmon instead of chicken, prepare the herby crumbs as instructed above, then pop the salmon fillets skin side down on a baking tray lined with baking paper. Prepare them the same way the recipe tells you to prepare the chicken above (you might not need all the mayo).

> Step 3 MOD: If you've got salmon, follow the step above, but the salmon only needs 12-15 mins in the oven. IMPORTANT: The salmon is cooked when opaque all the way through.

> Step 6 MOD: If you've got salmon, serve it alongside the potato and green beans.